<font color="#FF0000">HONORING THE PROTESTORS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 13:40:34 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
If we are to remember the Vietnam War with reference to American experiences, for me those with real courage during the war years were the men and women who went up against a nation, not those who so facilely went along with it under the unthinking justification of &quot;duty to country.&quot;  Those who just followed duty without question tragically paid for it; those who agreed with the war and fought assentingly got what they deserved.  Americans are so quick to (rightfully) shame the Germans for the holocaust, but see no moral parallels in the Vietnam War.  I don't see either the honor or the courage in those boys who simply complied in the interests of that thing called the &quot;national interest&quot; or &quot;duty to America.&quot;  That was the easy thing to do--what everyone else was doing.  There was no originality or independence of thought.  It was safe because it was what most everyone else was doing.  That banality of duty lead to slaughter.  Those who dared challenge the idea that such a war was in &quot;national interest&quot; were much more thoughtful and independent people, precisely in the tradition of the nation's founders and its best heroes.<br><br>
The greatest tragedy, to me, is that Americans still wish to remember the war with reference to their own experiences.  That is the ultimate national dishonor, for it is a self-reflection that prioritizes American humanity over.  Whatever religion or moral code one subscribes to, this is not appropriate adult behavior.<br><br>
To me the only good for America that came from the Vietnam War was a wake up call to Americans about the price of simple compliance rather than active citizenship and thoughtful engagement in policymaking. People died because they stopped the war later rather than sooner. Those who went off to Vietnam simply because the &quot;nation called&quot; without any independent conviction about its appropriateness practiced poor citizenship.<br><br>
Most of all, I am comforted to know that those who think that shipping off to the war and fighting and dying with pride and sense of duty were honorable will NEVER succeed in defining the experience of the War.  There are too many of us out here who see the honor in draft dodging, draft burning, protest and challenge to ignorant and immoral foreign policy.  As everyone knows, refusing to comply with evil is honorable; muddling along with it may produce tragedies of its own that require our compassion, but it is not honorable.
